data.content:
Here's the improved version using proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);                          // exact count check (subsumes > 0)
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);               // no null entries
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    CollectionAssert.Contains(users.Select(u => u.Role).ToList(), "Admin");
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `users.Count > 0` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Exact check subsumes it; failure message shows actual vs expected |
| `users.Count() == 3` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Shows *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"IsTrue failed"* |
| `admin != null` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(…)` | Expresses intent; avoids `Single` throwing before the assert |
| `users.All(…)` | add a message string | MSTest lacks a predicate-per-item assert, so keep `Assert.IsTrue` but **add a message** for diagnostics |

The general rule: prefer `Assert.AreEqual`, `Assert.IsNotNull`, and `CollectionAssert.*` over `Assert.IsTrue` — they produce far better failure messages.
